segments.text: Dr. Gammon, could you give me your full name and date and place of birth?
That's easy.
Full name.
First name, Samuel.
Sam for short.
Ray, R-H-E-A.
You try to spell that Ray, you get into trouble ordinarily.
What happened was, originally, that was R-E-A when that branch of family lived in Scotland.
Well they got in some kind of a religious row up there as the Scots are always doing and they finally moved over to Ireland and that's where they picked up the H in R-H-E-A.
And when were you born?
1889, 26 November.
And place of birth?
Southwest Virginia, county with W-Y-T-H-E
named for old man George who signed the Declaration of Independence.
I see.
Near any particular community or was this a farm or a... Small town, about possibly a thousand people at most.
I see.
Tom's name was Rural Retreat.
Rural Retreat.
Just off of the main highway which goes north of us for about a mile and can be so named that in making the long jaunt
for that day, 40 miles or so, between Wytheville, the county seat of our county, and Marion, the county seat of the next adjoining, Smith County.
When they got overtaken by bad roads and couldn't make it, they pulled off the main highway for about a mile to the south to this little settlement that came to be called Rural Retreat.
It's a very pleasant name.
Been that ever since.
In fact, it's on the northern one.
on the Norfolk and Western, so labeled on the railroad decision right now.
May I speak?
Sir, go ahead.
A friend, a cousin of ours, told him that he wouldn't for anything live in the town that sounded as though you were gargling when you gave the name.
Oh my goodness.
Could I have your full name, Mrs. Gammon, and your date, and place of birth?
Ellen.
Ellen?
Yeah, L-E-N.
Uh, maiden name R-O-T-H-E. Rothy?
Rothy.
Of Danish.
Danish extraction.
Which I'm proud of.
Her father and mother were both born in Denmark and at different times came over here and us went to marry them.
I see.
Yes, father came over because he was a child of old age and uh,
He had very few connections.
And it almost takes, in one of those countries over there, it almost takes a pool to get somewhere.
And so he did get somewhere, but he thought he'd have a better opportunity and had friends over here.
And so he came here.
And he was a distant, distant, distant cousin of my mother's.
My mother was tired of the small town
young men who were courting her, and she wanted to get away.
And she read the remark, oh, if I only knew anyone in America.
And an elderly cousin of hers said, why, you do, you know, the Henrietta, or Yetta, as they called her, Rothi, or Rothi, as they said in Denmark, with a R down there in the throat.
And so Mother wrote to this Henrietta Rothi,
And she, elderly, did not answer, but had her son answer.
And so my father answered.
And after a correspondence of a couple of years, during which period, he sent mother, what was that old?
A couple of old monthly magazines.
Century, I believe, is one.
And another one.
And mother had read a good bit of Shakespeare before she ever came over here, which you can't say for a good many of the people out there in it.
And it wasn't that nasty.
But that's true.
And so after some months, I would say about four months, they decided to marry.
And they were a very, very happy couple, weren't they Ray?
Yes, they were.
Dr. Gammon has often called my father a saint.
But he didn't look saintly.
He was well-built and always smiling.
But the Danes are like that, too.
They smile a lot.
You remember?
Yeah.
Where were you born?
I was born in Chicago, and I don't like it a bit.
But I couldn't help it.
My parents were there.
And your birthday?
I'm a few months older than Ray, so I'm bossing him now.
Dr. Gamow, do you remember anything from your childhood that stands out in your mind that might be of interest to you?
Yes, I think that I remember best when my father, knowing that it was part of Mother's plan.
Mother died when I was only six years old.
And part of her plan was that I should have a Shetland pony.
And he proceeded to get me one.
And I thought quite a lot of that pony, who did most everything to me that he shouldn't have done.
He bit me once and kicked me once and threw me several times.
Oh, my goodness.
His name was Sheik, S-H-E-I-K.
He came from the Sunnyside Pony Farm, Monmouth, Illinois.
I still remember that.
That's amazing.
And where did you two meet?
Beg your pardon?
Where did you and your wife meet?
In Baltimore.
In Baltimore.
Johns Hopkins Library.
And the library.
She was a librarian.
Oh, my goodness.
I said a library assistant is the correct name.
When I often say that I thought a great deal of Johns Hopkins and the value of that library.
And when I left, I knew I couldn't take the library, so I took the librarian as the next best bet.
We were married.
We were married.
He used to say, I corralled him there.
And I said, you didn't run very fast, so he changed it to say that he wanted to take the books, but he couldn't, so he took the librarian.
I think he got cheated on that.
Could you tell us about your education, say, beginning with when you first started formal schooling and, say, bringing it on to your Ph.D.?
Small country high school.
Where, in Virginia?
Virginia.
In Virginia?
Yes.
Rural Retreat High School.
Still doing business, the old stand.
Though I think it's deteriorated a good deal.
That's my private opinion, but that doesn't count.
That's your age, that's that.
Being an old man isn't what it used to be, I'd say.
And then did you go on to college immediately after high school?
After high school, I went straight to Washington League University at Lexington, Virginia.
And that town of Lexington is steeped in the reputation and lore and prestige of great men.
Robert Edward Lee, President of Washington Lee for five years.
Stonewall Jackson is buried there.
And you can't, well you can't tell those Lexingtonians very much about the Civil War or any of those fellas.
Oh my.
You've got your... Lee is buried there on the campus in the Memorial Chapel, which he built while he was president.
The mausoleum, where he and most of his family are buried right now, have been for years, is there on the campus.
It's a very beautiful crypt there.
And you were there for four years?
Five.
Five.
Not because I flunked, but because I got smart.
and crammed, loaded on, took my A.B.
in three years.
By the time I got through I wasn't so well satisfied with what I was getting out of it and so I took two more easy years for a master's degree.
I think I got more out of those last two than I did out of the first three.
You will note he didn't have to take the five years.
He elected to take them and could have gotten through with an A.B.
in
The three years, but he loaded too much.
And what were your specialties in history then?
Your favorites.
I think I liked possibly best, of course American history was always a favorite of mine.
As a youngster I read a great deal and my father with an eye on that saw that I had plenty of books.
I remember one Christmas I got 11 books
a set of three, Plutarch's Lives and numerous others.
My fondness for reading gave me a slant in the direction of history very naturally.
Then you went from Washington and Lee to Johns Hopkins or was there an interval?
No, after I finished in Lexington at Washington and Lee
I wanted to look around a bit.
I wanted to think a bit of what I was going to do next.
I thought I wanted to teach.
So I took, I waited for a while and in that while I took two years of teaching high school teaching.
Where were you teaching then?
At Austin College.
At Austin College, yes, up here at Sherman.
Because an old friend of my family

The man under whom I got my start in Greek was head of the Latin Greek department at Austin College and it was through his influence that I got the history department there at Austin College where I went in fall of 1922.
No.
Earlier.
Because we were married in 1918.
You must have gone there in 12.
Mm-mm.
No, no.
I was still in Washington, D.C. in 12.
Well, then you had two there before you came to Hopkins.
And Hopkins was 1912 is when you came to Hopkins.
Because you were there 13, 14, 15, 16.
No, 1912 to Hopkins.
Because you were there five years and then.
Yes, that probably was.
Yes.
And then on to John Hopkins then?
Or let's see.
Yes, actor Sherman.
Right.
Yep.
After prep school in there at Sherman College.
It was called Austin College in Sherman, but they had a prep department, and that is why Dr. Gammon said high school, but it was really better than high school.
That was a Presbyterian school, right?
It is.
Yes.
Still is.
Now, what made you decide to go back and work for a Ph.D.?
Well, if you were going, I could see easily enough.
But if you were going to get ahead in the teaching profession, you had to have more than an M.A.
M.A.s were just common speed tracks, so to speak.
Good M.A.s at that then.
And how long did you spend at Johns Hopkins?
I can tell you that.
It would be about four years.
No, it was there the total of five years.
Wait a minute.
You came in 19... Did you come there in 1913?
No, I came there in 1913.
Oh, that's what we're... Oh, my.
We're living in the present, you see.
So that's why we're a little hazy right in there.
But he had been there three years and then went off to...
This First World War, as we called it now, as we call it now, it was the war.
But now it's the First World War.
And he then got up to his first lieutenancy.
And then we were married at that time, when he was just a second Louis.
And then he came back after the war was over in his discharge as a first lieutenant.
and finished the two years to get his PhD degree.
See, I was watching then, so that's why I know it so well.
Where did you do most of your military service?
At Camp Lee.
Camp Lee in Virginia.
At Camp Hancock.
I was regimental personnel agent at Camp Hancock, Georgia.
But you were at Washington, over in Washington that day.
During the first two years of the war.
That's where you got lieutenancy.
over in Washington, what was the name of the place in Washington?
Because you used to commute and come over to court me.
So what's the name of the place?
Oh, that camp, Camp Lee, just outside of.
No, that's Petersburg.
Wait a minute, wait a minute.
Anyway, it's called Fort something now.
And right outside of Washington, everybody knows the place.
We can't remember.
And then he was caught at me right in there.
While he was there, it was just a, what, a 40-minute ride by train?
And officers counted the days.
That's it.
We were encouraged to light out at noon on Saturdays and not show up again the Monday.
And I'd grab the next train to Baltimore.
And then he came back.
Then he was sent to Camp Lee.
which was not too far away from Baltimore either.
So you see, the fates were against him and with me, as you see.
And he could come up there, but not quite as often.
And then he got sent to Camp Hancock down at a bus to Georgia.
And that was impossible, so he got too lonesome.
And I didn't like him being lonesome, so I decided that it was all right.
He asked me, of course.
to marry him.
So I thought it was all right.
I didn't want him to be lonesome.
I think that's why I married you.
Come to think of it.
Yes, Ellen came down on a train from Washington to Augusta.
I met the train.
And we went from there to the Presbyterian manse.
And we were married by Dr. Joe Sevier, Presbyterian minister for the First Church in Houston.
First Church in Augusta, I mean.
That's over, oh, they hopped out there, if you remember.
And you finished your Ph.D. in 1921?
No.
Finished his Ph.D.?
22 was the grade who you find listed in the Hopkins catalog, I think.
Oh, well, that's because it was... 1922.
Well, yes, because...
was finished then.
You know, I said, first he came.
I don't know why we're so hazy about that period.
Too long ago.
That's right.
No.
No.
He was there for three years, I think.
And then the war came.
And that kept him away for two years.
And during that period, we were married.
And then he came back.
And in 22, he got his PhD with that dissertation.
which is now being republished.
Then you went from there back to Austin College again after you got your PhD?
To the Collegiate Department.
Yes.
I had a little experience before that at Austin College as assistant to the principal of the prep department.
But this time they'd had a sample of me and thought they could stand it so they made me head of the history department, history and government.
Did you simply, how did you go about getting that job again?
Did you, after you finished your PhD, did you write them or write your friends that were still there?
Oh, no.
My friend was there on the job all the time.
He was head of the Latin Greek department.
And the president also knew the family.
See, they all came through that little plateau.
The president of Austin College then had his degree from King College of Bristol, Tennessee.
From Kingsport.
Which is next door to us.
And you were, how long were you at Austin College?
Four.
Four years.
Four years.
Came down here from there.
And how did you go about coming, how did it happen that you came to A&M?
Oh, better.
Well, they'd had a sample of me and thought they could stand it.
No, that was Austin College, but here.
Here at A&M.
How did you find out about...
He didn't.
He didn't.
No, people that had degrees...
or of any account, good degrees, don't go scrambling around for jobs.
They offered jobs.
I'll tell you how that was.
Charles E. Friley was dean of the School of Arts and Sciences here at A&M.
And it was through him.
They came looking for you?
He wrote to Hopkins, to various colleges, because he wanted a PhD.
Wanted a good PhD.
Yes, and so he got led to him.
We were in Virginia at the time for a week.
But in the summer, of course, summers, quite a few years.
And what did you do when you first came to A&M?
Were you open to the position?
Same thing I would still be doing if I were not retired.
Head of History Department.
You were hired as the head of the department.
Oh, yes.
I wouldn't have taken anything less.
Yes, I understand.
Because I was still a big boy up at Austin College.
I see.
And can you describe your...
First impressions, earliest impressions of the campus when you came and of the department?
I'm too busy.

I was quite adjustable, adaptable as taking in a new situation and it fitted how I was on the campus, our contacts, and the fact that Friday as dean of the School of Arts and Sciences gave me practically a free hand in organizing and
offering the course that I thought the Department of History should have.
So you made some changes when you came?
Not very radical.
I added some courses mostly.
Gave it a little broader reach.
Can you think of some of those that you added that you thought were necessary to the curriculum then?
Oh, I couldn't do that without a catalog.
Oh, I see.
That's all right.
I think I've been out of touch with it too long now.
Know it as well as I once did.
Mrs. Gammon, you were talking a moment ago about your impressions, some of the first impressions of the campus.
Could you tell us a little bit about those?
I didn't get that.
Please.
Could you tell us about your first impressions of the campus?
Yeah, at the campus here?
Yes, at the campus here at A&M.
Your first impressions.
You said it was friendly.
Could you?
Well, we've spent practically all our lives at educational institutions.
So I didn't think this was wonderful, nor did I think it was nothing.
I just took it for granted that it was like other colleges and universities, Johns Hopkins Universities and so on.
And we were rather pleased to be given a house right on the campus, both because of seniority and because, no not seniority, you didn't have any seniority then, but because of his position.
He was, the heads of departments had first choice, you see, and then professors and so on.
And as the seniority counted, too, you see.
Because once you got a house, you couldn't be pushed out of it.
And so we had that house that was painted green.
All the others were white.
And it stood opposite the, it stood where the parking lot now is for the Raleigh, whatever you call it.
Yes, right?
Opposite there.
Even the driveway that was the remains of an old road, we used it as a driveway to our garage.
It was the remains of an old road.
I don't know which one.
But long ago.
And probably before the college was starting.
It was a college then.
And it was rather pleasant to be right close
on the campus.
And those living on the campus had a certain prestige, too.
So I didn't know that, but I see that now.
And it was, we used the old college, what is now College Road.
That was the only way into town.
This Texas Avenue was just a muddy road.
And we never used it.
We went out by Westgate rather than by Eastgate.
And many people didn't have cars when they came, but we did.
We had bought a car up in Sherman and drove down here with our two boys.
And it was very pleasant to be on the campus because, as I said before, the people were very welcoming.
We didn't get hazed or beaten or anything like that because that system was in full swing when we came.
And one might say right in there that that was one of the drawbacks.
And they had it for quite a while, changing commandants and so on to get control of this.
I think it is all right now, especially since the women got in.
So there.
You're talking about the students hazing.
The students?
Yes, when you were talking about nobody, you said something about nobody beat you or anything.
Oh, no.
We weren't hazed.
No, it was just, I'm just taking off.
Oh, I see.
The student habit of hazing people.
I couldn't imagine them hazing the faculty.
No, they were the most welcoming, and we were not hazed in any way or made to feel new or anything like that.
No, I was just poking a little fun at the hazing system.
And I can't call it anything but the hazing system.
Once in a while.
Which lasted quite a long time and was a trouble to the administration.
Now, it didn't affect the other administrators.
That is, heads of departments were also administrative.
What were your impressions of the students that you taught, Dr. Gammon?
Put the marks around the mind, nothing very new about the type of preparation.
Well, they were-.
You didn't find them tremendously different from any that you'd ever taught before?
Because I'd had four year sampling of them at Austin College.
I thought maybe since you had been in the East you might have found them less well prepared or their backgrounds were not as good.
Well, I think I would make that as one of my impressions when I was first at Austin College.
that you got perhaps less well-prepared high school products.
But I make that rather hesitantly.
I would think that might have been a drawback because of the Texas rural school system at that time.
Students had missed probably a lot.
I think it was a drawback to the students.
Oh, yes, ma'am.
Not a drawback to the teachers, except that they had to work harder.
to put it through the skulls.
And, of course, here it was a school or college planned for a state college with cheaper tuition and so on.
And up in Austin College was a Presbyterian school, and Presbyterians are known to be pretty well educated, at least their ministry is, and we're Presbyterians.
There.
Who were some of the people who you were most closely associated with and remember most favorably in the early years?
All of them.
All of them.
Up there?
Here, up there.
Here, after we moved down here.
Mostly the Presbyterian group.
Yes, I think you're right.
Oh, our neighbors.
A few names.
Tell me their names, if you can.
Name some of them.
I can do that, I believe, better because I think women are more socially inclined.
I know that the Hedges, he was head of the chemistry department, lived right across the street from us.
And when we went to town or anyplace else, we'd go out our back door because we lived on corners.
And when Mrs. Hughes and I saw each other in town, we'd embrace just for fun because we...
Didn't see each other because we went out the back way.
But Ray helped Dr. Hedges when he had come.
He limped.
And he had been away for some surgery, perhaps.
But anyway, some attention.
And Ray met him and took him back to the campus.
So we knew them pretty well.
We knew the Seekies pretty well, Mr. Seekie.
He was a forester, a state forester, .
And I think you will find a good bit of records about him.
We were, of course, close to them.
We had young children, and they had an older boy who had retired.
did very, very well in his line of work and retired early in Slimington Street.
And then the people next door.
And Mrs. Hughes was giving a party.
And I remember she had a rooster she was going to make big, because it was a salad.
Chicken salad.
Chicken salad, rooster salad.
And it got away from her and her black coat.
And they were going around the house chasing it.
And meanwhile, we had a dog.
A fox terrier.
A terrier.
had adopted us.
We didn't seek him, just like we didn't seek this job here.
It came to us.
And so Dr. Gammon said, stranger, get him.
And a stranger.
We called him a stranger, because he came to us.
And so we just called him a stranger.
And he loved us very much, and we him.
And so he chased after the rooster, and just pinned the rooster down.
But that's what he was.
He had him by one wing, and that was it.
But Mrs. Hughes doesn't remember that.
She is, as I said, she just got her mind on a few things.
And let me see who else.
Oh, next door to them were the Reeds, which they were, we were at the same church, so we were pretty close there.
Then the other direction, next to the Seakeys, was the Leland's.
Leland, Leland.
And their boy and our boy played together.
Back of those two doors lived Dean Bolton.
And he had a young son and older children who was practically a sidekick of our children.
And Mrs. Bolton once said to me, she knew everything that happened in our house because she would hear it through Preston.
And she said, you've got an Encyclopedia Britannica.
That was the 1930 edition, I guess.

And when our children would play, if there'd be some subject come up that should be questioned, as for instance, George Washington telephoning to his lieutenants and captain, I think it was Samory that said, or Billy that said, telephoning wasn't invented.
Preston said.
Yes, it was so.
And so whoever it was, which of our two children, shot in and looked up in the inside computer.
We did not buy the book of knowledge and those other infantile things.
We gave them things that they'd have to work for to get their information.
And so he really convinced his playmate.
Now, that's another family.
Let's see, then there were the, we didn't know them too much, the Nuck Walkers.
And let's see, near them lived the Come and Dance.
We got to be quite friendly, I especially, with the Come and Dance wives.
I know they came to see us when they came back to college.
Two of them did.
And we had lost our older son then, and they remembered that.
And let's see who else.
Oh, of course, on the other end of the campus, we knew the Humberts very well.
In fact, Humbert was quite influential in getting our son out of the State Department a Rotary Fellowship.
And I always thought he came to us once, Dr. Humbert, and asked us, is there anything special you can tell us about Sam Ray?
He was called Sam Ray then.
combination of the two names.
And is there anything special you can tell him as a son?
I said, why, yes.
After we lost our son, our elder son, his brother, his elder brother, he wrote to us every day.
That's exactly what I wanted to know, said Dr. Humbert.
And of course, that sort of settled it.
I always told the Rotarians that they went around acting
as though he was their son, and we were just an institution.
So now, let me see.
And at the other end of the campus, beside the Humberts, there were, let's see, who do we know over there?
There was Cassians.
The Cassians.
SPEAKER 1.
Cassians was head of the YMCA for a long time.
SPEAKER 2.
Yes, he was the YMCA director, and had been at Austin College.
So Ray had some.
SPEAKER 1.
I had a finger in the pie getting him down here.
influence in putting in a good word for him here.
He was very much beloved.
He was a very genial sort of person.
Died in 52.
They, I suppose, were our closest friends, because we were Presbyterians together.
We'd been to Austin College together.
And our children, though hers, theirs, were younger.
Mason Lee Cashin is the younger of that.
And he is quite prominent.
He married
Dr. Walton's, no wait a minute, Dr. Walton's granddaughter, Ethel Walton Burgess's daughter, who is now the second Mrs. Cashin.
Let me see, who else was over there?
Of course the Marshes.
He was our doctor, Dr. J.E.
Marsh.
J.E.
Marsh, that's right.
He has a son who is Jack Marsh in practicing here, but he had died, but I think Mrs.
Marsh is still living.
Who else?
I have to think about the camels.
The camels were, he was head of the modern language.
And oh, I forgot this.
Some, he had a corner from us, the head of the English department.
And we became very good friends.
And when we moved out here, they put us off the campus so they could grow.
and put so many other buildings on the places where we lived.
They came and told you, you just have to move, right?
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, yeah, we just had to.
They gave us a little warning.
They didn't kick us out.
No, we didn't hear them, Lord.
They gave us, I think it was almost two years, because the semi's built down here, just on the next street.
And they were about, let's see, 91, about nine years older than we, no?
Five, six, seven, eight years older, I think I figured out.
And they have both died.
They were also from Virginia.
So you see, we had so much in common with them.
I don't know why I didn't mention them first.
Then there were people in the experiment station, especially, bless their souls, the Sherwoods lived off on the road
Jones Bridge, it was a Jones Bridge road they lived on, or the other road.
They went out to the experiment station, the farms out there.
But she was a great mixer, and we were very fond of them.
They died too early in 57, 58.
He died in 58, January 58, like the Harold Neckard.
And she later.
But they left.
It doesn't pay to leave a place where you've lived a long time.
Remember that, young man.
If you've settled down a long time in one place, your roots are so established, and your whole life is sort of woven in with the life of the community, that you unravel the fabric if you move.
We've seen a lot of that.
And you'll lessen your roots if you're uprooted.
Because we have seen many that have moved away and haven't lived long after that.
Now, whether there's any medical connection or whether anybody would agree with me, there must be a psychological sort of influence.
And so even though Delta Gamma had a good bit of property up there with County Virginia and in Smith County,
And we have always thought of going back to Virginia, even though we expected to freeze to death every winter.
The summers are glorious.
Yes.
Virginia is the southwestern part, and the altitude is around 3,000 feet.
You get sure enough winter there.
You're high up.
I spent four years in Norfolk, Virginia.
Oh, Norfolk?
That's a little more than sea level.
But we would go over there.
I spent my weekends in Williamsburg, and I enjoyed Williamsburg.
Oh, Williamsburg.
That's different.
I had to live in Norfolk because that's where I was in the service.
I didn't like Norfolk, but the rest of the state was beautiful, absolutely beautiful.
Especially the southwest.
Our section is the prettiest part of Virginia, right through there.
And that's where they, what's the name of that highway?
No, Blue Ridge, the new scenic.
road that runs down to Skyline Drive.
And that's very near to us.
But it deflects down into North Carolina a little before it gets to us up there.
So we had always been in there with a family.
And we would be near my family, who lived in the east.
And coming back to noticing.
the difference in the education of the young here that Eastern schools were better.
We could see that.
I could see it in all sorts of small ways.
Nothing you really could put your finger on, but in small ways.
I noticed it myself.
I was born in Chicago, that place.
And when I came, when my family moved east to Baltimore,
I had a hard time in, of all things, mathematics.
And now I'm doing the IRS for the family, which is sometimes pretty complicated.
So I remember that as a fact.
And let's see, we were talking about friends on the campus.
Oh yeah, you used to play golf with Dr. Walton, with President Walton.
Was it Richard?
Once in a while.
